# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: specialty-heap-zoo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] A **beap**, or **bi-parental heap**, is a data structure for a set (or map, or multiset or multimap) that enables elements (or mappings) to be located, inserted, or deleted in sublinear time.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] In a beap, each element is stored in a node with up to two parents and up to two children, with the property that the value of a parent node is never greater than the value of either of its children.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] Beaps are implemented using an array containing only the values to be stored, with the parent-child relationships being determined implicitly by the array indices.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] (That is: beaps are an implicit data structure.) In that respect they are similar to binary heaps, which are usually implemented that way as well.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] However, their performance characteristics are different from heaps; in particular, a beap enables sublinear retrieval of arbitrary elements.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] The beap was introduced by Ian Munro and Hendra Suwanda.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] A related data structure is the Young tableau.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] The height of the structure is approximately ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] Also, assuming the last level is full, the number of elements on that level is also ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] In fact, because of these properties all basic operations (insert, remove, find) run in $O({\sqrt {n}})$ time on average.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] Find operations in the heap can be $O(n)$ in the worst case.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] Removal and insertion of new elements involves propagation of elements up or down (much like in a heap) in order to restore the beap invariant.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] An additional perk is that beap provides constant time access to the smallest element and $O({\sqrt {n}})$ time for the maximum element.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] Actually, a $O({\sqrt {n}})$ find operation can be implemented if parent pointers at each node are maintained.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/beap] You would start at the absolute bottom-most element of the top node (similar to the left-most child in a heap) and move either up or right to find the element of interest.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In computer science, the **Brodal queue** is a heap/priority queue structure with very low worst case time bounds: $O(1)$ for insertion, find-minimum, meld (merge two queues) and decrease-key and $O(\mathrm {log} (n))$ for delete-minimum and general deletion.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] They are the first heap variant to achieve these bounds without resorting to amortization of operational costs.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Brodal queues are named after their inventor Gerth Stølting Brodal.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] While having better asymptotic bounds than other priority queue structures, they are, in the words of Brodal himself, "quite complicated" and "[not] applicable in practice." Brodal and Okasaki describe a persistent (purely functional) version of Brodal queues.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] A Brodal queue is a set of two trees $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ and 5 *guides*.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The definition of the guide data structure can be found in the following section.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For both trees, each node has a *rank*, this rank is useful for later operations and intuitively corresponds to the logarithm of the size of the subtree rooted in the node.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We note ${\text{arity}}_{i}(x)$ the number of children of the node x with rank i .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We will also use $t_{1}$ for the root of tree $T_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ for the root of tree $T_{2}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Here ${\text{NEXT-RANK-ARITY}}$ guarantees us that the size of the subtree rooted in a node is at least exponential to the rank of that node.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In addition, ${\text{ARITY-BOUND}}$ bounds the number of children of each rank for a given node, this implies that all nodes have rank and degrees in $O(\log n)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In a Brodal queue, not every node will have a bigger value than its parent, the nodes vialoating this condition will be called *violating nodes*.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] However, we want to keep the number of *violating nodes* relatively small.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] To keep track of violating nodes, we create for each node two sets $V(x)$ and $W(x)$ of nodes larger than x .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Intuitively, $V(x)$ are the nodes larger of x with large rank (such that $y\in V(x)$ if ${\text{rank}}(y)\geqslant {\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ ), and $W(x)$ are the nodes with small rank ( ${\text{rank}}(y)<{\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ ).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] These sets are implemented using doubly linked list meaning they have an order.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In particular, all violating nodes added to $V(x)$ are added at the front of the list, and all violating nodes added to $W(x)$ are inserted next to a node of same rank.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Since all nodes have rank in $O(\log n)$ the ${\text{W-RANK-BOUND}}$ and ${\text{V-RANK-BOUND}}$ , all $V(x)$ and $W(x)$ are in size $O(\log n)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We also have some invariants of the roots of the trees $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ : $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ (called the ${\text{ROOTS}}$ invariants).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The ${\text{V-SIZE-BOUND}}$ invariant essentially tells us that if we increase the rank of $t_{1}$ by one, we have at most $\alpha$ new "large" violations (here large means having a high rank) without violating the ${\text{V-RANK-BOUND}}$ invariant.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] On the other hand, the ${\text{W-ELEMENTS-RANK}}$ invariant tells us that all violations in $W(x)$ are "small", this invariant is true per the definition of W .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Maintaining the invariants ${\text{W-RANK-BOUND}}$ and ${\text{ROOT-ARITY}}$ is not trivial, to maintain these we will use the ${\text{DecreaseKey}}$ operation which can be implemented using a *guide* as defined in the next section.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] This definition is based on the definition from Brodal's paper.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We assume that we have a sequence of variables $x_{k},\dots ,x_{1}$ and we want to make sure that $\forall i\leqslant k,x_{i}\leqslant T$ for some threshold T .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The only operation allowed is ${\text{REDUCE}}(i)$ which decreases $x_{i}$ by at least 2 and increases $x_{i+1}$ by at most 1.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We can assume without loss of generality that ${\text{REDUCE}}(i)$ reduces $x_{i}$ by 2 and increases $x_{i+1}$ by 1.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If a $x_{j}$ is increased by one, the goal of the guide is to tell us on which indices i to apply ${\text{REDUCE}}(i)$ in order to respect the threshold.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The guide is only allowed to make $O(1)$ calls to the ${\text{REDUCE}}$ function for each increase.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] As long as after the increase of $x_{j}$ we have $x_{j}\leqslant x'_{j}$ we do not need to ask help from our guide since $x_{j}$ is "far" bellow T .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] However, if $x_{j}=x'_{j}$ before the increase, then we have $x_{j}+1>x'_{j}$ after the change.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] To simplify the explanation, we can assume that $T=2$ , so that $x'_{i}\in \{0,1,2\}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The guide will create *blocks* in the sequence of $x'_{i}$ of form $2,1,1,\dots ,1,0$ where we allow there to be no 1 .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The guide maintains the invariant that each element which isn't in a block is either a 1 or a 0 .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For example, here are the blocks for a sequence of $x'_{i}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We can destroy a block in time $O(1)$ by assigning $\bot$ to the memory cell pointed to by each element of the block.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] This way, the guide is able to decide which indices to ${\text{REDUCE}}$ in time $O(1)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] To reestablish the blocks, the pointers of the 1 and 0 added to the first block now point to the same cell as all the other elements from the first block, and the value of the second block's cell is changed to $\bot$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In the previous example, only two ${\text{REDUCE}}$ operations were needed, this is actually the case for all instances.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Therefore, the queue only needs $O(1)$ operations to reestablish the property.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] To implement the different priority queue operations we first need to describe some essential transformations for the trees.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] To link trees, we need three nodes $x_{1},x_{2}{\text{ and }}x_{3}$ of equal rank.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We can calculate the minimum of these three nodes with two comparisons.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Here we assume that $x_{1}$ is the minimum but the process is similar for all $x_{i}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We can now make the nodes $x_{2}$ and $x_{3}$ the two leftmost sons of $x_{1}$ and increase the rank of $x_{1}$ by one.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] This preserves all the ${\text{RANK}}$ and ${\text{SETS}}$ invariants.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If x has exactly two or three sons of rank ${\text{rank}}(x)-1$ , we can remove these sons and x gets the rank of its new largest son plus one.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] From the ${\text{ARITY-BOUND}}$ condition, we know that that the ${\text{NEXT-RANK-ARITY}}$ invariant will be preserved.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Then, all the ${\text{RANK}}$ and ${\text{SETS}}$ invariants remain satisfied.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If x has 4 or more children, we can simply cut of two of them and all the invariants remain true.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Therefore, the delinking of a tree of rank k will always result in two or three trees of rank $k-1$ (from the 2 or 3 children cut off) and one additional tree of rank at most k .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] When we add and remove sons of a root, we want to keep the ${\text{ROOT-RANK}}$ invariant true.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For this purpose, we use 4 guides, two for each roots $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] To have constant time access to the son of $t_{1}$ we create an extendible array of pointed that has for each rank $i\in \{0,\dots ,{\text{rank}}(t_{1})-1\}$ a pointer to a son of $t_{1}$ of rank i .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The sons of $t_{1}$ of rank ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-1$ and ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-2$ are treated separately in a straight forward way to maintant their number between 2 and 7.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The equivalent to the $x'_{i}$ variable in the definition of the guide will have the values $\{5,6,7\}$ for the higher bound guide and $\{4,3,2\}$ for the lower bound.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In this context, when we add a child of rank i to the root, we increase $x'_{i}$ by one, and apply the ${\text{REDUCE}}$ operations.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The ${\text{RECUCE}}(i)$ operation here consists of linking three trees of rank i which creates a new child of rank $i+1$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If this increase results in too many sons of rank ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-2$ or ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})-1$ we link some of these sons together and possibly increase the rank of $t_{1}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If we increase the rank of $t_{1}$ , we have to increase the length of the extendible array managed by the guides.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Cutting off a son from $t_{1}$ is very similar, except here the ${\text{REDUCE}}$ operation corresponds to the delinking of a tree.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For the root $t_{2}$ the situation is nearly the same.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] However, since ${\text{MINIMUM-NODE}}$ guarantees us that $t_{1}$ is the minimum element, we know that we won't create any violation by linking or delinking children of $t_{1}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Linking sons will never create new violations but the delinking of sons can create up to three new violations.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The tree left over by a delinking is made a son of $t_{1}$ if it has rank less than ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ and otherwise it becomes a son of $t_{2}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The new violations which have rank larger than ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})$ are added to $V(t_{1})$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] To maintain the invariants on the $V(t_{1})$ set (namely ${\text{V-RANK-BOUND}}$ and ${\text{V-SIZE-BOUND}}$ ), we have to guarantee that the rank of $t_{1}$ will be increased and that $\alpha$ in those invariants is chosen large enough.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The goal of this transformation is to reduce the total amount of potential violations, meaning reducing $\left|\bigcup _{x\in T_{1}\cup T_{2}}V(x)\cup W(x)\right|$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We assume we have two potential violations $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ of equal rank k .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Because of ${\text{ARITY-BOUND}}$ , we know that both $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ have at least one brother.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Else, $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are brothers of a node we will call y .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Else, $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are the only children of rank k of y ..
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We will cut off $x_{1},x_{2}{\text{ and }}y$ , the new rank of y will be one plus the rank of its leftmost son, We replace y by a son on $t_{1}$ of rank $k+1$ , which can be cut off as described in the previous subsection.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If the replacement for y becomes a violating node of rank $k+1$ , we add it to $W(t_{1})$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Finally we make $x_{1},x_{2}{\text{ and }}y$ new sons of $t_{1}$ as described above.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The only violation sets where we will add violations are $V(t_{1})$ and $W(t_{1})$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] As described above, the invariants on those sets are maintained using guides.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If there are more than 4 violations which are sons of $t_{2}$ , we cut the additional violations off and link them below $t_{1}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] This removes the violation created by these nodes and doesn't affect the guide maintaining the sons of $t_{2}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For each priority queue operation that is performed, we increase the rank of $t_{1}$ by at least one by moving a constant number of sons of $t_{2}$ to $t_{1}$ (provided that $T_{2}\neq \emptyset$ ).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Increasing the rank of $t_{1}$ allows us to add violations to $V(t_{1})$ while still maintaining all our invariants.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Otherwise, we cut off a son of $t_{2}$ of rank ${\text{rank}}(t_{1})+2$ , delink this son and add the resulting trees to $t_{1}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If $T_{2}=\emptyset$ , we know that $t_{1}$ is the node of largest rank, therefore we know that no large violations can be created.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] ${\text{MakeQueue}}()$ just returns a pair of empty trees.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The tree having the minimum root becomes the new $T_{1}$ tree.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If this tree is also the tree of maximum rank, we can add all the other trees below as described previously.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In this case, no violating node is created so no transformation is done on violating nodes.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Otherwise, the tree of maximum rank becomes the new $T_{2}$ tree and the other trees are added below as described in the section "Maintaining the sons of a root".
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If some trees have equal rank to this new $T_{2}$ , we can delink them before adding them.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The violations created are handled as explained in the section : "Avoiding too many violations".
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] ${\text{DecreaseKey}}(Q,e,e')$ replaces the element of e by $e'$ (with $e'\leqslant e$ ).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If $e'<t_{1}$ , we swap the two nodes, otherwise, we handle the potential new violation as explained in the section "Avoiding too many violations".
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] ${\text{DeleteMin}}(Q)$ is allowed to take worst case time $O(\log n)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] First, we completely empty $T_{2}$ by moving all the sons of $t_{2}$ to $t_{1}$ then making $t_{2}$ a rank 0 son of $t_{1}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Then, $t_{1}$ is deleted, this leaves us with at most $O(\log n)$ independent trees.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The new minimum is then found by looking at the violating sets of the old root and looking at all the roots of the new trees.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] If the minimum element is not a root, we can swap a root from a tree of equal rank to it.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Then, we make the independent trees sons of the new minimum element by performing $O(\log n)$ linking and delinking operations.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] This reestablishes the ${\text{RANK}}$ and ${\text{ROOTS}}$ invariants.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] By merging the V and W sets of the new root along with the V and W sets of the old root together, we get one new violation set of size $O(\log n)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] By doing at most $O(\log n)$ violation reducing transformations we can make the violation set only contain at most one element of each rank.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] This set will be our new W set and the new V set is empty.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] This reestablishes the ${\text{SETS}}$ invariants.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] We also have to initialise a new guide for the new root $t_{1}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Here, $-\infty$ denotes the smallest possible element. ${\text{Delete}}(Q,e)$ can simply be implemented by calling ${\text{DecreaseKey}}(Q,e,-\infty )$ followed by ${\text{DeleteMin}}(Q)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In this section, we summarize some implementation details for the Brodal Queue data structure.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Due to its high amount of pointers and sets to keep track of, the Brodal Queue is extremely hard to implement.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For this reason it is best described as a purely theoretical object to lower time complexity on algorithms like Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] However, the Brodal has been implemented in Scala (the GitHub repository can be found here: https://github.com/ruippeixotog/functional-brodal-queues).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] In his paper, Gerth Stølting Brodal mentions that: "An important issue for further work is to simplify the construction to make it applicable in practice".
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/brodal-queue] Gerth Stølting Brodal is a professor at the University of Aarhus, Denmark.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A **bucket queue** is a data structure that implements the priority queue abstract data type: it maintains a dynamic collection of elements with numerical priorities and allows quick access to the element with minimum (or maximum) priority.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In the bucket queue, the priorities must be integers, and it is particularly suited to applications in which the priorities have a small range.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A bucket queue has the form of an array of buckets: an array data structure, indexed by the priorities, whose cells contain collections of items with the same priority as each other.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] With this data structure, insertion of elements and changes of their priority take constant time.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Searching for and removing the minimum-priority element takes time proportional to the number of buckets or, by maintaining a pointer to the most recently found bucket, in time proportional to the difference in priorities between successive operations.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The bucket queue is the priority-queue analogue of pigeonhole sort (also called bucket sort), a sorting algorithm that places elements into buckets indexed by their priorities and then concatenates the buckets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Using a bucket queue as the priority queue in a selection sort gives a form of the pigeonhole sort algorithm.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Bucket queues are also called **bucket priority queues** or **bounded-height priority queues**.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] When used for quantized approximations to real number priorities, they are also called **untidy priority queues** or **pseudo priority queues**.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] They are closely related to the calendar queue, a structure that uses a similar array of buckets for exact prioritization by real numbers.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Applications of the bucket queue include computation of the degeneracy of a graph, fast algorithms for shortest paths and widest paths for graphs with weights that are small integers or are already sorted, and greedy approximation algorithms for the set cover problem.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The quantized version of the structure has also been applied to scheduling and to marching cubes in computer graphics.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The first use of the bucket queue was in a shortest path algorithm by Dial (1969).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A bucket queue can handle elements with integer priorities in the range from 0 or 1 up to some known bound C, and operations that insert elements, change the priority of elements, or extract (find and remove) the element that has the minimum (or maximum) priority.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] It consists of an array A of container data structures; in most sources these containers are doubly linked lists but they could alternatively be dynamic arrays or dynamic sets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The container in the pth array cell *A*[*p*] stores the collection of elements whose priority is p.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In this way, insertions and priority changes take constant time, and extracting the minimum or maximum priority element takes time *O*(*C*).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] As an optimization, the data structure can start each sequential search for a non-empty bucket at the most recently-found non-empty bucket instead of at the start of the array.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This can be done in either of two different ways, lazy (delaying these sequential searches until they are necessary) or eager (doing the searches ahead of time).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The choice of when to do the search affects which of the data structure operations is slowed by these searches.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Dial's original version of the structure used a lazy search.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This can be done by maintaining an index L that is a lower bound on the minimum priority of any element currently in the queue.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] When inserting a new element, L should be updated to the minimum of its old value and the new element's priority.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] When searching for the minimum priority element, the search can start at L instead of at zero, and after the search L should be left equal to the priority that was found in the search.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Alternatively, the eager version of this optimization keeps L updated so that it always points to the first non-empty bucket.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In either of these two variations, each sequential search takes time proportional to the difference between the old and new values of L.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This could be significantly faster than the *O*(*C*) time bound for the searches in the un-optimized version of the data structure.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In many applications of priority queues such as Dijkstra's algorithm, the minimum priorities form a monotonic sequence, allowing a monotone priority queue to be used.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In these applications, for both the lazy and eager variations of the optimized structure, the sequential searches for non-empty buckets cover disjoint ranges of buckets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Because each bucket is in at most one of these ranges, their numbers of steps add to at most C.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Therefore, in these applications, the total time for a sequence of n operations is *O*(*n* + *C*), rather than the slower *O*(*nC*) time bound that would result without this optimization.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Another optimization (already given by Dial 1969) can be used to save space when the priorities are monotonic and, throughout the course of an algorithm, always fall within a range of r values rather than extending over the whole range from 0 to C.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In this case, one can index the array by the priorities modulo r rather than by their actual values.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The search for the minimum priority element should always begin at the previous minimum, to avoid priorities that are higher than the minimum but have lower moduli.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In particular, this idea can be applied in Dijkstra's algorithm on graphs whose edge lengths are integers in the range from 1 to r.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Because creating a new bucket queue involves initializing an array of empty buckets, this initialization step takes time proportional to the number of priorities.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A variation of the bucket queue described by Donald B.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Johnson in 1981 instead stores only the non-empty buckets in a linked list, sorted by their priorities, and uses an auxiliary search tree to quickly find the position in this linked list for any new buckets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] For example, consider a bucket queue with four priorities, the numbers 0, 1, 2, and 3.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] It consists of an array A whose four cells each contain a collection of elements, initially empty.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] For the purposes of this example, A can be written as a bracketed sequence of four sets: $A=[\emptyset ,\emptyset ,\emptyset ,\emptyset ]$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Consider a sequence of operations in which we insert two elements x and y with the same priority 1, insert a third element z with priority 3, change the priority of x to 3, and then perform two extractions of the minimum-priority element.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A bucket queue can be used to maintain the vertices of an undirected graph, prioritized by their degrees, and repeatedly find and remove the vertex of minimum degree.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This greedy algorithm can be used to calculate the degeneracy of a given graph, equal to the largest degree of any vertex at the time of its removal.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The algorithm takes linear time, with or without the optimization that maintains a lower bound on the minimum priority, because each vertex is found in time proportional to its degree and the sum of all vertex degrees is linear in the number of edges of the graph.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This variant of Dijkstra's algorithm is also known as Dial's algorithm, after Robert B.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The same idea also works, using a quantized bucket queue, for graphs with positive real edge weights when the ratio of the maximum to minimum weight is at most c.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In this quantized version of the algorithm, the vertices are processed out of order, compared to the result with a non-quantized priority queue, but the correct shortest paths are still found.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In these algorithms, the priorities will only span a range of width *c* + 1, so the modular optimization can be used to reduce the space to *O*(*n* + *c*).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A variant of the same algorithm can be used for the widest path problem.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In combination with methods for quickly partitioning non-integer edge weights into subsets that can be assigned integer priorities, it leads to near-linear-time solutions to the single-source single-destination version of the widest path problem.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The set cover problem has as its input a family of sets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The output should be a subfamily of these sets, with the same union as the original family, including as few sets as possible.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] It is NP-hard, but has a greedy approximation algorithm that achieves a logarithmic approximation ratio, essentially the best possible unless P = NP.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This approximation algorithm selects its subfamily by repeatedly choosing a set that covers the maximum possible number of remaining uncovered elements.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A standard exercise in algorithm design asks for an implementation of this algorithm that takes linear time in the input size, which is the sum of sizes of all the input sets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This may be solved using a bucket queue of sets in the input family, prioritized by the number of remaining elements that they cover.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Each time that the greedy algorithm chooses a set as part of its output, the newly covered set elements should be subtracted from the priorities of the other sets that cover them; over the course of the algorithm the number of these changes of priorities is just the sum of sizes of the input sets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The priorities are monotonically decreasing integers, upper-bounded by the number of elements to be covered.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Each choice of the greedy algorithm involves finding the set with the maximum priority, which can be done by scanning downwards through the buckets of the bucket queue, starting from the most recent previous maximum value.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] The total time is linear in the input size.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Bucket queues can be used to schedule tasks with deadlines, for instance in packet forwarding for internet data with quality of service guarantees.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] For this application, the deadlines should be quantized into discrete intervals, and tasks whose deadlines fall into the same interval are considered to be of equivalent priority.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] A variation of the quantized bucket queue data structure, the calendar queue, has been applied to scheduling of discrete-event simulations, where the elements in the queue are future events prioritized by the time within the simulation that the events should happen.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In this application, the ordering of events is critical, so the priorities cannot be approximated.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] To keep these searches fast, this variation attempts to keep the number of buckets proportional to the number of elements, by adjusting the scale of quantization and rebuilding the data structure when it gets out of balance.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] Calendar queues may be slower than bucket queues in the worst case (when many elements all land in the same smallest bucket) but are fast when elements are uniformly distributed among buckets causing the average bucket size to be constant.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] In applied mathematics and numerical methods for the solution of differential equations, untidy priority queues have been used to prioritize the steps of the fast marching method for solving boundary value problems of the Eikonal equation, used to model wave propagation.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] This method finds the times at which a moving boundary crosses a set of discrete points (such as the points of an integer grid) using a prioritization method resembling a continuous version of Dijkstra's algorithm, and its running time is dominated by its priority queue of these points.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] It can be sped up to linear time by rounding the priorities used in this algorithm to integers, and using a bucket queue for these integers.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] As in Dijkstra's and Dial's algorithms, the priorities are monotone, so fast marching can use the monotone optimization of the bucket queue and its analysis.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/bucket-queue] However, the discretization introduces some error into the resulting calculations.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] A **calendar queue** (CQ) is a priority queue (queue in which every element has associated priority and the dequeue operation removes the highest priority element).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] It is analogous to desk calendar, which is used by humans for ordering future events by date.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Discrete event simulations require a future event list (FEL) structure that sorts pending events according to their time.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Such simulators require a good and efficient data structure as time spent on queue management can be significant.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] The calendar queue (with optimum bucket size) can approach O(1) average performance.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Calendar queues are closely related to bucket queues but differ from them in how they are searched and in being dynamically resized.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Theoretically, like a bucket queue, a calendar queue consists of an array of linked lists.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Sometimes each index in the array is also referred to as a bucket.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] The bucket has specified width and its linked list holds events whose timestamp maps to that bucket.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] A desk calendar has 365 buckets for each day with a width of one day.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Each array element contains one pointer that is the head of the corresponding linked list.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] If the array name is "month" then month[11] is a pointer to the list of events scheduled for the 12th month of the year (the vector index starts from 0).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] The complete calendar thus consists of an array of 12 pointers and a collection of up to 12 linked lists.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] In calendar queue, enqueue (addition in a queue) and dequeue (deleting from a queue) of events in FEL is based on event time.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Let the calendar queue with *n* buckets with *w* width.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Then enqueue of an event with time *t* operates on bucket ${\frac {t}{w}}\mod n$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] And more than two events scheduled in the bucket according to the increased timestamp.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] To dequeue events from the calendar queue, it keeps track of current year and day.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Then it searches for the earliest event within that bucket and dequeue it.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] If the number of events in the queue is much smaller or much larger than the number of buckets, it will not function efficiently.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] The solution is to allow the number of buckets to correspondingly grow and shrink as the queue grows and shrinks.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] The number of buckets is doubled or halved each time the *Ne* (number of events) exceeds 2*Nb* or decreases below *Nb*/2 respectively.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] When *Nb* is resized, the new width *w* has to be calculated as well.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] The new *w* that is adopted will be estimated by sampling the average inter-event time gap from the first few hundred events starting at the current bucket position.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/calendar-queue] Thereafter, a new Calendar queue is created and all the events in the old calendar will be recopied over.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] A **Kinetic Heap** is a kinetic data structure, obtained by the kinetization of a heap.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] It is designed to store elements (keys associated with priorities) where the priority is changing as a continuous function of time.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] As a type of kinetic priority queue, it maintains the maximum priority element stored in it.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] The kinetic heap data structure works by storing the elements as a tree that satisfies the following heap property – if *B* is a child node of *A*, then the priority of the element in *A* must be higher than the priority of the element in *B*.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] This heap property is enforced using certificates along every edge so, like other kinetic data structures, a kinetic heap also contains a priority queue (the event queue) to maintain certificate failure times.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] A regular heap can be kinetized by augmenting with a certificate [*A*>*B*] for every pair of nodes*A*, *B* such that *B* is a child node of *A*.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] If the value stored at a node *X* is a function f*X*(*t*) of time, then this certificate is only valid while f*A*(*t*) > f*B*(*t*).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] Thus, the failure of this certificate must be scheduled in the event queue at a time *t* such that f*A*(*t*) > f*B*(*t*).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] All certificate failures are scheduled on the "event queue", which is assumed to be an efficient priority queue whose operations take O(log *n*) time.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] When a certificate [*A*>*B*] fails, the data structure must swap *A* and *B* in the heap, and update the certificates that each of them was present in.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] Thus, assuming non-degeneracy of the events (no two events happen at the same time), only a constant number of events need to be de-scheduled and rescheduled even in the worst case.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] Kinetic heaps perform well according to the four metrics (responsiveness, locality, compactness and efficiency) of kinetic data structure quality defined by Basch et al.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] The efficiency of a kinetic heap in the general case is largely unknown.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] However, in the special case of affine motion f(*t*) = a*t* + b of the priorities, kinetic heaps are known to be very efficient.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] In this special case, the maximum number of events processed by a kinetic heap can be shown to be exactly the number of edges in the transitive closure of the tree structure of the heap, which is O(*n*log*n*) for a tree of height O(log*n*).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/kinetic-heap] If *n* insertions and deletions are made on a kinetic heap that starts empty, the maximum number of events processed is $O(n{\sqrt {n\log n}}).$ However, this bound is not believed to be tight, and the only known lower bound is $\Omega (n\log n)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] In computer science, a **soft heap** is a variant on the simple heap data structure that has constant amortized time complexity for 5 types of operations.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] This is achieved by carefully "corrupting" (increasing) the keys of at most a constant number of values in the heap.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Other heaps such as Fibonacci heaps achieve most of these bounds without any corruption, but cannot provide a constant-time bound on the critical *delete* operation.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] The amount of corruption can be controlled by the choice of a parameter $\varepsilon$ , but the lower this is set, the more time insertions require: expressed using Big-O notation, the amortized time will be $O(\log 1/\varepsilon )$ for an error rate of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Some versions of soft heaps allow the *create*, *insert*, and *meld* operations to take constant time in the worst case, producing amortized rather than worst-case performance only for findmin and delete.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] As with comparison sort, these algorithms access the keys only by comparisons; if arithmetic operations on integer keys are allowed, the time dependence on $\varepsilon$ can be reduced to $O(\log \log 1/\varepsilon )$ or (with randomization) ${\textstyle O({\sqrt {\log \log 1/\varepsilon }})}$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] More precisely, the error guarantee offered by the soft heap is the following: each soft heap is initialized with a parameter $\varepsilon$ , chosen between 0 and 1/2.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Then at any point in time it will contain at most $\varepsilon \cdot n$ corrupted keys, where n is the number of elements inserted so far.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Note that this does not guarantee that only a fixed percentage of the keys *currently* in the heap are corrupted: in an unlucky sequence of insertions and deletions, it can happen that all elements in the heap will have corrupted keys.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Similarly, there is no guarantee that in a sequence of elements extracted from the heap with *findmin* and *delete*, only a fixed percentage will have corrupted keys: in an unlucky scenario only corrupted elements are extracted from the heap.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] When a key is corrupted, the value stored for it in the soft key is higher than its initially-given value; corruption can never decrease the value of any key.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] The *findmin* operation finds the minimum value among the currently stored keys, including the corrupted ones.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] The soft heap was designed by Bernard Chazelle in 2000.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] The term "corruption" in the structure is the result of what Chazelle called "carpooling" in a soft heap.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Each node in the soft heap contains a linked list of keys and one common key.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] The common key is an upper bound on the values of the keys in the linked list.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Once a key is added to the linked list, it is considered corrupted because its value is never again relevant in any of the soft heap operations: only the common keys are compared.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] This is what makes soft heaps "soft"; one cannot be sure whether any particular value put into it will be corrupted.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] The purpose of these corruptions is effectively to lower the information entropy of the data, enabling the data structure to break through information-theoretic barriers regarding heaps.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Despite their limitations and unpredictable nature, soft heaps are useful in the design of deterministic algorithms.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] For instance, they have been used to achieve the best complexity to date for finding a minimum spanning tree.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Other problems whose efficient solution has been simplified using soft heaps include finding the k th smallest element in several classes of structured sets of values, including heap-ordered trees, sorted matrices, and sumsets.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] After the comparison step of the algorithm, the first of the two subsets contains all of the deleted keys, so it includes at least $n/3$ elements.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Among the $2n/3$ elements that were not deleted, at most $n/3$ are corrupted, so at least $n/3$ are uncorrupted.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] These uncorrupted and undeleted elements must all belong to the second subset, because they are greater than or equal to the soft heap's (possibly corrupted) value of L , which is in turn greater than the true value of L .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Thus, both subsets have between 33% and 66% of the elements.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/soft-heap] Because each level of recursion reduces the problem size by a constant factor, the total time of the algorithm can be bounded by a geometric series, showing that it is $O(n)$ .
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In computer science, a **weak heap** is a data structure for priority queues, combining features of the binary heap and binomial heap.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] It can be stored in an array as an implicit binary tree like a binary heap, and has the efficiency guarantees of binomial heaps.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] A weak heap is most easily understood as a heap-ordered multi-way tree stored as a binary tree using the "right-child left-sibling" convention.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In the multi-way tree, and assuming a max-heap, each parent's key is greater than or equal to (≥) all the child keys (and thus, by induction, all members of the subtree).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The last condition is a consequence of the fact that an implicit binary tree is a complete binary tree.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The structure of this tree maps very neatly onto the traditional 1-based (Ahnentafel) implicit binary tree arrangement, where node k has a next sibling (left child) numbered 2*k* and a first child (right child) numbered 2*k* + 1, by adding an additional root numbered 0.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] This root has no siblings, only a first child, which is node 1 (2×0 + 1).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] This structure is very similar to that of a binomial heap, with a tree of height h being composed of a root plus trees of heights *h* − 1, *h* − 2, ..., 1.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] A perfect (no missing leaves) weak heap with 2*n* elements is exactly isomorphic to a binomial heap of the same size, but the two algorithms handle sizes which are not a power of 2 differently: a binomial heap uses multiple perfect trees, while a weak heap uses a single imperfect tree.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Weak heaps require the ability to exchange the left and right children (and associated subtrees) of a node.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In an explicit (pointer-based) representation of the tree, this is straightforward.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In an implicit (array) representation, this requires one "reverse bit" per internal node to indicate which child is considered the left child.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] A weak heap is thus not a strictly implicit data structure since it requires *O*(*n*) additional space (⁠1/2⁠ bit per node).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] However, it is often possible to find space for this extra bit within the node structure, such as by tagging a pointer which is already present.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In the implicit binary tree, node k with reverse bit *rk* has parent ⌊⁠*k*/2⁠⌋, left child 2*k* + *rk*, and right child 2*k* + 1 − *rk*.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Viewed as a multi-way tree, each node in a weak heap is linked to two others: a "next sibling" and a "first child".
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In the implicit tree, the links are fixed, so *which* of the two links is the sibling and which the first child is indicated by the reverse bit.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Note that *every* node in a weak heap can be considered the root of a smaller weak heap by ignoring its next sibling.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Nodes with no first child are automatically valid weak heaps.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] A node of height h has *h* − 1 children: a first child of height *h* − 1, a second child of height *h* − 2, and so on to the last child of height 1.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] These may be found by following the first child link and then successive next sibling links.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] It also has next siblings of height *h* − 1, *h* − 2, etc.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] A node's parent in the multi-way tree is called its "distinguished ancestor".
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] To find this in the binary tree, find the node's binary parent.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] If the node is the right child (first child), the parent is the distinguished ancestor.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] If the node is the left child (next sibling), its distinguished ancestor is the same as its binary parent's.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In the implicit tree, finding the binary parent is easy, but its reverse bit must be consulted to determine which type of child the node is.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Although the distinguished ancestor may be log2*n* levels high in the tree, the *average* distance is 2.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] (It's at least 1, and half of the time we recurse, so *D* = 1 + *D*/2, meaning that *D* = 2.) Thus, even a simple iterative algorithm for finding the distinguished ancestor is sufficient.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Like binomial heaps, the fundamental operation on weak heaps is merging two heaps of equal height h, to make a weak heap of height *h*+1.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] This requires exactly one comparison, between the roots.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Whichever root is greater (assuming a max-heap) is the final root.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Its first child is the losing root, which retains its children (right subtree).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The winning root's children are installed as siblings of the losing root.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] This operation can be performed on the implicit tree structure because the heaps being merged are never arbitrary.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] At the beginning, the heap invariants apply everywhere *except* possibly between the first root and its distinguished ancestor.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] All *other* nodes are less than or equal to their distinguished ancestors.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] (The first root is greater.) The first root's binary children (first child and next sibling) are exchanged (using the reverse bit), and then the first root and its distinguished ancestor are exchanged (by copying).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The second case works because, in the multi-way tree, each node keeps its children with it.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The first root is promoted up the tree because it is greater than its distinguished ancestor.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Thus, it is safely greater than all of the ancestor's previous children.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The previous ancestor, however, is not a safe parent for the first root's old children, because it is less than the first root and so it's not guaranteed to be greater than or equal to all of its children.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] By swapping the binary children, the appropriate subset of the demoted ancestor's old children (which are safely less than or equal to it) are demoted with it.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The demoted ancestor's new siblings are the first root's old children, promoted, which are safely less than or equal to the promoted first root.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] After this operation, it is uncertain whether the invariant is maintained between the new distinguished ancestor and *its* distinguished ancestor, so the operation is repeated until the root is reached.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Weak heaps may be used to sort an array, in essentially the same way as a conventional heapsort.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] First, a weak heap is built out of all of the elements of the array, and then the root is repeatedly exchanged with the last element, which is sifted down to its proper place.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] A weak heap of n elements can be formed in *n* − 1 merges.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] It can be done on various orders, but a simple bottom-up implementation works from the end of the array to the beginning, merging each node with its distinguished ancestor.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Note that *finding* the distinguished ancestor is simplified because the reverse bits in all parents of the heaps being merged are unmodified from their initial state ("not reversed"), and so do not need to be consulted.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] As with heapsort, if the array to be sorted is larger than the CPU cache, performance is improved if subtrees are merged as soon as two of the same size become available, rather than merging all subtrees on one level before proceeding to the next.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Sifting down in a weak heap can be done in *h* = ⌈log2*n*⌉ comparisons, as opposed to 2 log2*n* for a binary heap, or 1.5 log2*n* for the "bottom-up heapsort" variant.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] This is done by "merging up": after swapping the root with the last element of the heap, find the last (height 1) child of the root.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Merge this with the root (its distinguished ancestor), resulting in a valid height-2 heap at the global root.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Then go to the previous sibling (binary parent) of the last merged node, and merge again.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Repeat until the root is reached, when it will be correct for the complete tree.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] In a weak max-heap, the maximum value can be found (in constant time) as the value associated with the root node; similarly, in a weak min-heap, the minimum value can be found at the root.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] As with binary heaps, weak heaps can support the typical operations of a priority queue data structure: insert, delete-min, delete, or decrease-key, in logarithmic time per operation.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Sifting up is done using the same process as in binary heaps.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] The new node is added at the leaf level, then compared with its distinguished ancestor and swapped if necessary (the merge operation).
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] This is repeated until no more swaps are necessary or the root is reached.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Variants of the weak heap structure allow constant amortized time insertions and decrease-keys, matching the time for Fibonacci heaps.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] Weak heaps were introduced by Dutton (1993), as part of a variant heap sort algorithm that (unlike the standard heap sort using binary heaps) could be used to sort n items using only *n* log2*n* + *O*(*n*) comparisons.
[src:specialty-heap-zoo/weak-heap] They were later investigated as a more generally applicable priority queue data structure.
